,Not Recommended,233290,29689030,Posted: 4 February,all,WHAM,"Murdered: Soul Suspect has a really cool premise. You're dead, a ghost, and you need to figure out who killed you. You can walk through walls, do poltergeisty stuff, read people's minds, woo!In reality, the game is mostly just wandering around surprisingly small maps, picking up a seemingly endless pile of collectables that serve as plot-filler and as a source for some spooky ghost stories.Also, since you're a ghost and still cannot walk through some doors (because the writers of the game wrote themselves into a corner) you need a living person to help you, and that person is one of the most annoying 15-year-old goth-teenage girls I have ever seen in a videogame. Yaay for cringe!Beyond walking around, touching things and reading people's minds, the only form of gameplay is avoiding and destroying demons in an oversimplified stealth minigame followed by a QTE. On the whole, the gameplay is not very engaging and solving some of the scenes flawlessly requires you to do quite a bit of the old ""what was the game dev thingking about here"" -mindgames.For a murder mystery plot, the game has way too few characters and the clues are too obvious to keep the game interesting.The game also seems to have a low number of voice actors, resulting in samey characters, and for some reason it also seems the game devs made precisely four character models: ""man"", ""woman"" ""girl"" and ""scary little girl"" (five if you count the demons) and went with those, so all the people in the game have the exact same body types and... It feels weird. Like they're all clones, milling about endlessly.All in all, Soul Suspect falls flat despite a cool premise and the game isn't really very enjoyable.Playtime: 6+ hours (Single playthrough)Ratings (1-10)Visual: 6Audio: 7Story: 4Gameplay: 6Overall: 5"
76561197992229015,Recommended,233290,34468127,Posted: 24 August,all,Dire,"M:SS is a unique sort of adventure game. There's not really any action in the game, no brawling, no shooting, nothing, so if you're looking for that, don't bother. If you want to experience a supernatural detective story, however, you may feel right at home. The game does a lot of things right, but doesn't always hit the mark.You play as a kid-with-troublesome-past-turned-detective-ghost. The meat of the game is exploration and solving ""the Bell killer case"". In order to do that you can explore the main hub area of the game, Salem, as well as about 7 or so levels. All of these can be freely explored and revisited once you've unlocked them in the story (I think you can even resume the game after beating it to collect everything). Speaking about collectibles, those are undoubtedly what will - hopefully - capture your attention the most, since the main game itself is abysmally short if you just rush through. It took me about 8 hours to finish it and I've found about 95% of the collectibles. Most notably are the ghost stories, one of which you can find in every level including Salem. For these you just have to reveal and collect specific items, some of which are very well hidden, to unlock a narrated short story. It's actually kinda fun to listen to them. Of course, if you're lazy, you can just look them up on YT...Apart from that there are scenes from your life, notes from your dead wife, notes about the killer, etc. I'd say the notes about your past with your wife are probably the most interesting, the rest is ok-ish, but it's nothing that would make the story better. The other stuff at least makes you care a bit about Ronan.The main gameplay mechanic, however, is finding clues and solving cases. I gotta be honest here, there's nothing much to it. You basically just go around the room, look for interactions, listen to the narration and put 2 and 2 together. Most of these cases are very logical, however, finding some clues or interpreting them correctly can just be a case of trial and error in my opinion, which doesn't really make this mechanic all that great. Luckily that doesn't impede your progress (unless you can't find the relevant clues), just your ""score""...you can try as often as you want and there are no up- or downsides to it from a gameplay viewpoint.The most outstanding feature of the game is probably that, since you're a ghost, you can walk through walls and such. The game feels like an old school FPS with no clip mode activated. Lovely, but it can also be disorientating, and your ghost form can't cross all thresholds. Each level is also at some point populated by demons (3 or 4), who patrol an area in a set radius. If they spot you, you better hide. You can either completely ignore them and rush through most areas or take your time to stalk them yourself and dispatch them with an easy button press...it's, frankly, quite boring and clearly a mechanic that was tacked on. At least it feels like it. And that's a general problem with the game: it feels fresh, but also at times unfinished. There ""could"" have been so much more, but instead it's just a glorified item collector with a pretty decent story (which imho is the main attraction here). For example, you can also help some ghosts find their final rest, but with most you can just ""ask them a question"" and that's it...or just talk to them, but they don't have anything to say. That just feels weird. I mean, what's with the questioning? It feels as if the devs intended to do more with that but either ran out of time or budget or just scrapped the feature for another reason and left these remainders in the game.Visually the game is also not a stunner, despite using the Unreal 3 engine. Since the game plays at night anyway, and you're dead...there's very little colour, very little distinction. It just feels a bit ""bland"", but you could argue that was intended and fits the theme...still, it feels so boring and most locations don't have that ""oh, this is cool"" feeling to them.There's also a few bugs and movement issues at times, as well as severe performance issues that shouldn't be there in a game such as this. Luckily they don't impact the gameplay at all, but they're still annoying. Not sure if it's the game's fault or Win 10's.I'd say wait for a deep sale and give it a whirl."
,Recommended,233290,31512840,Posted: 2 May,all,Shyguy,"I have mixed feelings about this game.Pros:- This is, first and foremost, a 3D point-and-click game, and as an avid fan of the genre I found it most enjoyable.-Great atmosphere, with various extensive areas that have plenty of explore-value. You can breeze through this game if you prefer, or take your time and explore everything (I chose the latter and was not disappointed).-On numerous occasions you get to possess and play as a cat.-Loads of easter eggs and collectables if you're into that stuff (I am)-A lot of narrative was written into this game that is only accessible through the aforementioned collectables. If you get bored by excess backstory then you don't have to engage with it, but if you are into it there's a lot there to enjoy.-Great game for achievement hunters, though many achievements involve the collectables.Cons:-The protagonist is- you guessed it- a jaded, white, flowy brown haired, fedora wearing, tattoo bearing, cigarette smoking dude with a 2edgy4you past and a serious chip on his shoulder. Tbh I'm pretty over this character as it's been done time and time again, and no amount of swaggering, sauntering, or side-smirking is going to make me feel like this character is in any way original or interesting.- Some awkwardly timed voice-acting means characters cut each other off on occasion, which I found very distracting in an otherwise immersive game.- Although the story was decent, it definitely got a bit cliche at times (it takes place in Salem, Massachusetts so I'm sure you can imagine half the plot off the bat). There are plot twists meant to keep you interested but that didn't stop me from figuring out what was going on long before the protagonist did.- Not enough ghosts for you to talk to, and far too many living people who have nothing interesting to say.I do recommend this game if you're a fan of point-and-clicks and ghost stories, though I don't think I could recommend getting it at full price. Even a slight sale will probably be worth the value, as you can easily get 8-10 hours of gameplay out of this game if you don't rush straight through the main story."
