,Recommended,233290,13021802,"Posted: 20 November, 2014",all,Pointnclickster,"I haven't felt the need to review for a while, but I can't help but talk about this game. For those of you who have played the Blackwell series (look at my review), I feel that Square Enix programmers played the games and thought, ""Hey, we can make a non-P&C, grittier, updated graphics version of Blackwell!"". In some respects, it really feels that way. A ghost needs to solve his own murder, plus help lost ghosts solve their issues so that they can move on with the help of a medium. Only instead of Roseangela we get a whiny teenager by the name of Joy. The crime solving isn't that difficult, but when the story is this enjoyable who really cares? The game takes place in Salem, and I feel that the town is one of the big stars of the game. The developers knew they had a lot to work with and they did a great job. You get to discover artifacts that uncover Salem's dark history, uncover artifacts that reveal haunting stories, and help ghosts piece together their untimely end. The main characters are a mixed bag. Ronan, is a detective who spent most of his life on the wrong side of Lady Law before joining the force. He's a great character. His sidekick is a gothic emo of a teenager named Joy. I see why they think she needs to be here, but I just didn't like her that much. Luckily, she only appears as much as she needs to, leaving you free to take your time between levels to explore Salem and backtrack for achievements or artifacts if need be. For you artifact and achievement junkies, there is a ton to find. Most will be able to find a lot of the stuff, in the first playthrough, but it is worth playing again. I highly recommend this supernatural detective game."
76561198028124018,Not Recommended,233290,31524554,Posted: 3 May,all,ThatMarvellousHoni,"Long story short, a gorgeous game with a clever concept let down by some dumb decisions and strange logic.(This short review may contain very minor spoilers)Before we kick off: I'm an idiot. If you were a murderer, you would move to the town I'd worked in to just do what you wanted with a terrified populace as I walked constantly into doors and fell down stairs. However I managed to feel 'smarter' than Soul Suspect. Gameplay is mostly walking around a room finding clues and pressing 'X', before summing up the five last minutes by selecting the three or so clues that answer the question asked at the start. You can't move out of the investigation area so I found myself wandering around waiting for the big X symbol to leap onto my screen. You found a diary page! Let's delve into the tortured life of- oh wait. It's one saying ""Diary page of your wife"". No story, not even an abridged paragraph. Maybe 10 seconds of spoken dialogue and that's your lot.Without doubt, Soul Suspect is a lovely looking thing. The buildings and weather are all beautifully rendered, but the people walking around look like mannequins. You can read their minds as well, hopefully offering an insight into- oh no, it's just two or three pre-set phrases.The concept is great. Solve your own murder? Find peace for restless spirits? Wicked. Spooky! Intriguing! But... not quite. Know what I mean? I found an old timey ghost crying on the beach who remembered nothing of how she died save a boat and a name. All the clues needed to complete this were within five feet of her. Just open your damn eyes! It's like it'strying so hardto be clever but just can't quite get there. The relevant clues are all painfully obvious so it becomes a slightly flat point'n'click without the charm of a point'n'click.As for the combat, let me help you out: use the ability to see through walls, wait for three seconds, sneak up behind the (admittedly quite cool looking 'demons') and kill them off. There is nothing else to it.I could go on but I'm sure you haven't got this far. If you have, you solved a mystery which is as hard as any puzzle in this game. If you want (like I did) an interesting mystery to solve, try the remastered Full Throttle. Want more humour? Monkey Island. Want a spooky puzzle? The Room and its sequel. They'll do a much better job than this.I soWANTEDto like and recommend the game, but despite the theme, there's no...Spirit."
