76561198004419232,Not Recommended,233290,31756603,Posted: 14 May,all,Happiness Officer,"You might like if:You want to pace your way through a good story without much focus on the game itself.""Oh cool! Solving the mystery of your own murder. So it's a puzzle game... but with ghosts!""If only.""Missed opportunity"" is perhaps the best way to describe this one. It's not a bad game by any means, but the problem is the lopsided execution of stunning graphics with next-to-no gameplay. The concept is fantastic, but the banality of the actual meat of the game is downright bizarre. You have an adult story sitting on top of a children's educational game that teaches them the importance of nouns.If you're not too fussed about the gameplay though, this should be a decent bet as the writing and visuals are incredible. It's gorgeously dark and atmospheric, and the characters are engaging enough to have you care about them, despite being a little stereotypical. The twists and turns were very well executed and, if nothing else, was worth a playthrough to enjoy the full story. It's no Ghost Trick (for any DS fans out there), but was clever nonetheless.The problem is that the actual gameplay felt like an afterthought that was slapped on in order to give you something to actually do. You don't so much ""solve puzzles"" more ""repeat the question"" - You're given the scenario of ""ah! I can read this person's mind to find out more about my murder. But what can I do to jog their mind about my murder? What can I make them think about... in order to get more details on my murder?""Answer: ""My Murder""Seriously...? I put this down to being a tutorial, but this actually is how most of the puzzles in the game rolls. Others include a flashback of a terrified person being slaughtered with the caption ""This person is _____"" and you have to choose between adjectives like ""Bloody terrified"", ""Bored"" or ""On the brink of sexual ecstasy""... What is this? A mash-up of Reader Rabbit and Hercule Poirot?I'm not done yet.The ""investigation"" scenes involve you finding clues... which consist of walking around a room until you see the 'Interact' prompt appear, at which point you mash the interact button and be told why this clue is important. Collect all 20 and you can proceed by picking the key clues out of the ones you found, forcing you to make the difficult decision of deciding whether to follow possible leads from a murder weapon or a tin of blue paint.And then we get to the daemons. Bloody terrifying on first appearance and sends a shiver down your spine as you hear their screech, but ultimately become more of a story-blocking hassle than an actual threat. You can hide from them by hopping between conveniently-located hiding places (random husks floating indiscriminately in the middle of nowhere) which basically mean you play whack-a-mole with a daemon until you can sneak up on them and trigger the button combo to exorcise them (I recommend a controller here, as the keys are a bit awkward for exorcising on the WASD setup). If you fail... back to whack-a-mole until they get bored and patrol their little square route again.The final attempt to flesh out the game are random items dispersedall over the place... with no real incentive to collect the lot other than completionism, ghost stories and reading memoirs from Julia going ""Ronan is such a bad boy with his smoking... but he's well fit"".It's such a shame. Unfortunately a good story just isn't enough to hold the game on its own. It screams of potential but feels like a hollowed-out remnant of what could have been an incredible title."
