,Recommended,233290,16508598,"Posted: 18 June, 2015",all,RaxuZz ZiRtaeb,"You can possess a cat just because of that, the game is worth to pay for, + the environment and the stories about the characters, is just amazing!!!!"
,Recommended,233290,20819618,"Posted: 28 January, 2016",all,dudz_fryd,"As the game begins we find Ronan exploding out of a shattered 4th story window after a confrontation with a shadowy figure.  He awakens to find himself temporarily disembodied but that state soon becomes permanent upon the arrival of the Bell Witch Killer.  Shot 7 times with his own gun, Ronan must now solve the mystery of his own murder and in the process uncover dark secrets that have haunted Salem for centuries.Quite a build up eh?It is and it's worthy of it.  The story is intriguing with twists, turns and dead ends to thrill any devotee of the mystery genre.  Add in a tastefully done horror component supported by an eerie backdrop of a dark and gloomy Salem complete with lost souls, haunted houses, and frightful demons.The game is gorgeous even on my creaky old gaming laptop ( circa 2008 ) and the controls simple.  You're led on a path similar to the Call of Duty campaign modes on the hunt for clues to your own murder.  On the way you'll find ample opportunity to complete side quests but be warned if like me you seek to earn all of the Steam achievements you must be methodical in your approach.  For me it took 2 playthroughs as there is no quicksave nor any way to go back once you've completed the final chapter of the game.It's a casual game but it can be maddening at times.  For one, you have no onscreen map nor any way to mark your progress toward achievements.  Meaning you'll spend a lot of time running in circles to find the way forward and backtracking for that one elusive clue.Then there's the demons.  I understand that a game in the horror genre has to have some kind of threat but they're all over the place.  It breaks the flow of the narrative and it's jarring to go from a casual detective story to a flurry of button mashing every 10 minutes.Still, even with the more ""gamey"" aspects, it's still more ghost story than game which explains some of its mechanical shortcomings.  My first playthrough was simply for the sake of taking it all in.  The second was purely for my own desire to see everything and in the process earn every Steam achievement.All tolled I've spent a bit over 30 hours and enjoyed every minute of it."
76561198038625342,Recommended,233290,12808619,"Posted: 5 November, 2014",all,Dash,"Crank your noir machine up to an 11!  This game has more noir atmosphere and characters then any game in the history of videogames!  Too bad it has a ridiculous amount of problems as well.  Before I go into those problems, I just want to reiteriate that I lovedddddddd the noir atmosphere and did really enjoy my time with the game. From the creepy haunted house to the crazy insane asylum this game just drips with noir atmosphere (but seriously wtf I wanted to go to that lighthouse the whole game and it never happened, why have a creepy lighthouse that I can't go to!)  It's almost exactly what I wanted ""Wolf Among Us"" to be.First of all it's important to know that this is an adventure game through and through.  It has no combat (it has a couple of extremely easy stealth puzzles), it kind of has 1 quick time event, but really it's just you walking around.  In fact I'm not even sure if the ""puzzles"" qualify as puzzles.  The main game mechanic is searching for clues to solve the mystery.  You do this by examining the environment until you come across a button prompt showing you it's a clue, you then take those clues and try and put them in the right order to solve the current ""puzzle.""  It has no fail state, so you can just click on things until you get the right order.  I'd say that is one of the games biggest failings.  It would have been great if you didn't know how many clues you need and could come to the wrong conclusions as you went through the game eventually causing you to solve the ultimate mystery incorrectly.  However, everything is rather straight forward.I'm also very confident that this game was simply unfinished.  You more or less have an open world to walk around in, yet the game only has about 4 or 5 side quests.  I can't imagine that this is all they wanted to have when they set out to make this game.  The fact that the game also ranks you on how you solve the ""puzzles"" also leads me to believe originally their was more to it and you could solve the puzzles incorrectly without the game just stopping.  The plot also starts to come apart towards the end.  The cast of characters seems just silly small for a murder mystery and almost none of these characters are developed at all.  I can only assume they wanted to go more into these characters if they had time.  Despite all that, I enjoyed the central story and loved the atmosphere and the mechanic of searching for clues, and I just really wanted more of everything.  The fact it ends in 7 hours is just ludicrous and unforgiveable at a price of $50, I bought it for $12 which I thought was way too much.  #Worth $5"
