,Recommended,233290,12718194,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,SETHEN,"A game that tends to never stay dead.  Murdered: soul suspect is an interesting title, that pins the main character Ronan O'Connor into a murder mystery.  During the early part of the game it becomes certain that you are the victim of a soon to come unraveling tale that goes to show, there's more to Salem that one might think.  The gameplay by far is slow throughout the game but is then overshadowed by side missions and collectibles that consume most of your time within Salem.  My one annoying gripe with the game, is the amount of clues thrown into the environment.  During one mission, I found myself walking around in a endless circle looking for a small object that wouldn't represent the button action until the camera was faced in the correct directional path that game set out.  But given the small annoyance of the clue system, the story overall out ways any issues within the game.  teleportation is a key thing later on in the game, in which you gain the ability to fast travel larger amounts of space and allows you to traverse none accessible areas.Rating:  7/10Recommend:  YesGood:+Story+Graphics+Side Missions / Collectibles+The CatBad:- Clues- Claustrophobic areas that lend little to the camera"
,Recommended,233290,16238918,"Posted: 7 June, 2015",all,Eisenreich,"I can see how this game might disappoint others, as there is so much more it could do as a survival horror and as a detective game, but for what it is, I think this is a brilliant game, and there are enough items and secrets to find to give it replay value. I guess because of the different path options of another certain ""poltergeist simulator"" if you like i.e. Beyond Two Souls it is often a shame when I play games like this now and there aren't multiple endings (even Silent Hill 2 had different endings on replays), but I guess we are a little spoilt, and this isn't trying to be a David Chase or a Deus Ex game.The idea itself was so novel and appealing I knew I had to grab this eventually, it reminded me of the basic premise of the old PS2 game Shadow of Memories in which you travel back in time to solve your own murder. In this moody, supernatural almost LA Noire style of setting I knew I couldn't resist. It wasn't until I played it I realised it's all set in Salem, so given that the backstory and local folklore have a large presence in this game, this was one hell of a bonus for me given my interest in the witch hunts and magic.The music and atmosphere didn't disappoint. The backstory and tragic history is incorporated into it very well, and the way in which this game combined supernatural elements with crime scene investigation was really inventive and original.  As said, there are things you can miss as well, but this is mostly side missions. I guess few games if any have really matched LA Noire in this department.The graphics look great, can't fault the voice acting either. In terms of the horror elements, as a puzzle game it's challenging enough, but seeing the same ghouls everywhere gets very repetitive very quickly, and it just becomes a chore of running, hiding and timing. It's different enough but just has no variety, still I can see how hard it is to do something really novel and inventive with the ghost-themed survival horror format. Especially if you are a ghost yourself.Overall great game worth getting, worth experiencing and worth playing again, just don't be too disappointed by the length and lack of variety in gameplay....Salem does allow for some exploration, though."
