76561198002555011,Recommended,233290,13823188,"Posted: 3 January, 2015",all,MattyVanHalen,"Murdered: Soul Suspect is a game where you play as a detective named Ronan, who dies during a chase for the Bell Killer, who has been killing young women of Salem, Massachusetts.  Ronan is your typical cliche chain-smoking detective, wearing the fedora and vest, and talking with a low, raspy voice.In M:SS, you have constant flashbacks of how you died, and you need to figure out why, because you find out you are stuck in a limbo spirit world, and will be stuck there forever until you find out what you need to find out.  As you solve these cases of the Bell Killer killings to ""release your soul"", you travel through Salem as a ghost, able to walk through many walls and obstacles, viewing the real world as it progresses (without you) and spirits trapped as you are, along with ghostly residue of things that have happened in the past.As a ghost detective, you will solve cases and ask questions of other ghosts and spirits, find clues at crime scenes and put cases together, and use an abundance of ghost abilities, such as possession, transportation, and reading minds, to name a few.M:SS is a very unique game of the supernatural, and pretty interesting, but it has many flaws that ruin the flow of the game.  While playing detective can be very fun to a lot of crime solvers, the method in which you solve these crimes is a bit silly.  You simply inspect all the clues in the surrounding area, then ""solve"" the portion of the case by piecing it together with the clues you found.  The problem is, it's like putting together a puzzle where all the pieces are numbered and fool-proof...so it doesn't feel like you are solving much of anything.The worst and most obnoxious part of the game, however, is the combat system.  Yes--the combat system--as a ghost.  Occaisonally, you will come across demons, and you must use stealth to take them out with a clunky, button-sequenced execution mechanic.  If you fail, you have to retreat and hide in ""ghost residue"" until they leave.  The combat could have been completely been left out and it would have made the game better.However, even with the terrible combat system, and the goofy crime scene mechanics, the story is interesting and the collectibles you find are fun to read.  I recommend this game, but not very high, and only for about $15-20 or less.  All in all, I rate the game a 7.0 out of 10."
