,Recommended,233290,11606755,"Posted: 8 August, 2014",all,The_Hairless_Ginger,"firstly i want to highlight that this game has some truly great writting. i mean bioware levels of good writting. the core story of this game is that you play detective Ronan O'Connor who is murdered investigating a serial killler in the twon of Salem. the story follows the detectives journey to discovere the identity and reason for his murder assissting others along the way .first thing i want to say is that this game has a very heavy L.A Noire feel. if you didnt like L.A noire then you wont like this and vice versa if you like it then Murdered: Soul Suspect is the game for you. the core factors of this game are the story and the investigations. being a police officer the investigation skills were always going to play a big part in this game. the first investigation is very basic as to act as a tutorial to the player. the investigations are the primary form of gameplay with the player having to use their initiative to search the scene for clues and piece togethor what has happened. finding the clues themselves is not as simple as you'd think either with some of the investigations requiring a thourough search to find all the pieces of the pouzzle. for example in an investigation in the towns museum i found most of the clues fairly easily but the last clue proved to be a real pain in the♥♥♥♥♥♥. a painting hidden deep behind a shelf covered with boxes to obscure it, even worse the room was dark and the painting is black. i only managed to find the clue after about 30 minutes of searching and a lot of cursing haha. but even though the game can be a difficult at points it has a great sense of rewarding when you finish an investigation and unlock another piece of the puzzle.another asoect that is important in this game is the mechanics, admittadly in a game where that focus's more on makingthe player think than the character being pushed to the limit the mechanics are as expected very solid, basics are obviously solid, running, looking, and interacting with objects are the core of the game but there is a few other core mechanics that are done quite well. as a ghost detective O'Connor has the abillity to interact with otherworldly objects in the town of Salem such as floors, walls, doors, staircases and ramps. this can be a diffficult mechanic to get right as the character is basically adding in game enviroment (i've developed a few games and tried to do this myself its not as easy as it sounds aha) but Square Enix have gotten it right here with a seamless addittion to the enviroment at the instruction of the player opening up new parts of the town. the other mechanic done well is the teleportation mechanic (not a spoiler as you see other ghosts doing this straight off the bat) the teleporting is only short range to avoid you jumping all the way over town in one go. it takes a few seconds to charge up but it comes in handy at points when looking for clues. the only mechanics i take issue with are the possession mechanics. now these work pretty well but its not as well rounded as the other mechanics, it can be a bit difficult to focus on the person you are trying to possess sometimes which made me slightly irritated to be honest.the story writting for this game is as i said though VERY well done. what this game is, is essentially an interactive  detective thriller novel. the story plays out just as you'd expect but with some very well placed twists. i guarantee if you play this game you will guess wrong about the identity of the killer. the various games twists are very well placed but none more than the end .. no spoilers .. but it is very well placed and just about the last thing i expected playing this game.finaly i shall examine the look of this game. the graphics for this game are very pretty but not overwhelmingly stunning. for the pc it isnt the best i quality i was expecting. it has a more console feel in terms of graphics which isnt really a bad thing. it doesn't do anything to damage the feel of the game as it still looks very good, the cinematics are nicely done keeping a similair graphical level to the game itself which i think works better for the way the game transitions from cut scene to actual gameplay. i would love to see this game with a more beautiful asthetic look to enhance aspects such as the moving through wiast high objects or to make Detective O'Connor himself maybe a bit easier on the eye.in short i very much reccomend this game if you are looking for a good story and to make yourself think a bit more than the usual game. the story will engross you while the investigations and the twists will keep you guessing until the game is ready to reward you with answers. there is also a hint of sarcy dry humour that i liked from Ronan which i think makes him more likeable but you can make your own mind up about that. i reccomend this game as a solid 8/10 .. its very good but not flawless and i doubt you will regret giving it a play"
