76561198061355625,Not Recommended,233290,10464884,"Posted: 13 June, 2014",all,TheSurrealTruth,"While I enjoyed the game enough to actually finish it, the overall experience felt very unpolished.What I Liked:-Lovable Characters: I liked all the characters. The voice acting was really great, and I cared about Ronan and Joy; a lot of fun and interesting interactions between the two of them.-A completionist's dream: All sorts of stuff to collect, and fun little stories to unlock if you're into that sort of thing.-Interesting Storyline: The story was surprisingly original, outside of a few painfully predictable points. Original or not, it was interesting and kept my playing.What I Hated:-Sloppy Game Mechanics: Game mechanics were a mess. Especially the dialogue options. You enter a cutscene for each dialogue choice, and the break is very obvious. Once the cutscene ends, there's another obvious break, and you get to choose another dialogue option. It was strange and killed the immersion.-Investigations: Basically a hidden objects game. Walk around, find anything and everything it actually lets you examine until it says you've found all the clues. Then guess which one is relative to the current case. Easy and oh-so boring.-Felt Unfinished: A lot of the powers were pretty useless save for one or two very rare, very unique moments where the game practically screams at you: USE THIS POWER! Teleportation could've been really cool, but there's only a few spots it actually comes in handy, and even then it's super clunky and annoying.A lot of useless hiding spots you'll never use, no matter what, never ever. They're just there for the aesthetics, I guess? Just looked messy to me. And while the start of the game seems to promise a lot of interesting side investigations -- helping to put spirits to rest -- there are very few to actually be found as the game progresses, at least, that I could find.-Enemies: Demons. . .could've been scary, but instead they're just annoying. They walk (float?) a predetermined route. You do the exact same thing to kill them (quick time event). There's no real combat in the game, or even a sense of urgency. You just hide, quick-time kill an enemy when he turns his back on you, repeat.-Cats: O. . .M. . .G Fun at first, but then, seriously, WHY is the SAME black cat everywhere in Salem? You know what, I think that friggin cat might be the killer! Shows up in the most convenient places, always there when I need it. . .what's it playing at? Or maybe it's different cats, all brothers and sisters. . .with absolutely no way to tell them apart. . .? Maybe? And seriously, what is the point of pressing ""Q"" to ""Meow""?I enjoyed the game, it was fun in its own ways. Mostly it was a story that was nice to experience. But MURDERED: Soul Suspect is NOT a $50 game. Maybe $20. So no, can't recommend it."
