,Not Recommended,233290,10495194,"Posted: 16 June, 2014",all,friscote,"This game is quite unusual in comparison to the others, and that's the main point of its success. The options are unusual: you can possess, influence on smbd, read the mind and execute the demons. You walk through the game as a ghost, and the main objective is to solve your murder. Despite of this, you are also able to solve the other victim's murders while revealing the hidden items. After you found all the clues on a particular problem, the game proceeds with the next video part that tells you smth. more about your own. AND THAT'S ALL. Nothing more. It becomes boring, especially for those who do not like repetitive cycles. There is nothing scary in the game, it just makes you bored. My advice is: buy this game only if you like what I described above or if you are reach enough to spent around $60 to explore HQ video and the graphics and to satisfy your curiosity."
,Not Recommended,233290,10926417,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Mr. Octopicake,"This game cuts a lot of corners, and in a bad way. I will start off by saying that you shouldn't expect anything innovative in terms of gameplay and story because there is literally nothing to this game. Have you played Heavy Rain or Beyond Two Souls? Remember how there was some gameplay in that? Take that,  but remove more of the gameplay and make it a noclip simulator 2014 edition because all you'll  be doing is walking around and looking at things. Slight spoilers ahead.The detective bits? Bland, and obvious as the story is. Sure you won't figure out who the killer is but you will pick up what the deal is with the Killer and still have the protagonist and everyone else bumping their heads into the walls being clueless. Anyone could of picked up the patterns since it was so obvious but near the end of the game that you'll be eager for it to end. Unless you're easy to please. Oh there's a twist to the plot but it doesn't make any gatdam difference to the plot nor does it change anything at all for the later part.Now let's get to gameplay, aka wonder around a building trying to navigate and occassionally posessing people just to influence. There's no point in posessing other people that aren't vital to the ""INVESTIGATE ZONE"" since they all have two lines in mind read and that's it. Reused model heads on different bodies and that's it, find a creeper ghost in some kid's closet only to find five more of him with multiple jobs. Investigate zones are what I like to call areas that you'll be trying to search every nook and cranny to find enough clues to conclude the level, and that itself is also really annoying. Most of the clues are hard to see, and I understand how it is but if I have to look hard through one big room just to realize I need to examine some bloody cat prints for no reason that aren't even remotely related to the case then what's the point? This game is more hollow than how I felt when I beat it.As for the supposed combat? Horrible. There's nothing to it, and it's the most bland thing you'll ever experience. The demons that you face are always set on a path, they won't hunt you down unless they see you nor explore any rooms other than the patrol paths that they'll never stray from. Killing them is also a chore. Press direction + button = instant victory. That's all to it. They're just there to hinder you and nothing else. They'll arrive in the area you just left and have to backtrack to because they can. You can't get by them either so you have to fight them. You can hide and wait patiently. It just feels like they threw them in there just ""because."" They don't have any real point to them other than to add more than just walking around and ""examine"" things.There are side quests though, and that's just more INVESTIGATE ZONES for you to burn time away in to make the game last longer. Will you get anything for it? No. There are collectables, will you get anything for it? No. Only thing you will get is achievements, and  that's it. There are no rewards, there's no good feeling having to help ghosts and frustrate yourself in INVESTIGATE ZONES that are so damn open or have clues so hidden that you can't complete it. A good example is one quest where you have to find out if a guy killed his friends or not, and the objective is ""Who saw the driver?"" No one in that area, not even the Taxi cab driver who was probably called the other night. There's no point in any of these side quests, nor the collectibles to find out ""Salems history"" or backstory.If I want to read about Salem's obvious history that I learned in history class, I'll use gatdam google3/10Don't buy it unless it's on sale for like ten bucks."
,Not Recommended,233290,10920560,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,AntiAntagonist,"A fun premise: solving your own murder, possessing cats and being able to walk through walls.Too bad investigation is simply a treasure hunt followed by a guessing game.  Walking through walls sounds like it should be freeing, but the majority of walls in this game are unpassable which makes the entire experience strangely claustrophobic.This feels like a game whose design had many more elements, but wasn't given the resources to expand much beyond the primary gameplay elements.For a game whose plot is so central I would have hoped to have more twists and turns.  Instead I guessed the ending halfway through the incredibly short storyline.I hope whoever did the visual design for the characters gets put on another project as their work was one of the few saving graces."
