,Not Recommended,233290,14593761,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,Katosepe,"Throughout my playthrough of Murdered: Soul Suspect, I could never truly figure out if this was just a game that took the modern game developer's philosophy of all-inclusiveness to an extreme or if they honestly just think gamers are all dumb as posts. That's the biggest problem with this game. I'm generally a fan of story-based games and can appreciate when they make games decently easy to complete so that you can follow the story at a good pace. Even for me, Murdered: Soul Suspect was so ridiculously easy that I just couldn't bring myself to care.You follow the story of Ronan, a cop working on a serial killer case in the city of Salem. As the game starts, Ronan meets his grisly end but comes back as a ghost. He quickly finds out that in order to move on to the afterlife with his beloved, he must solve the case of the Bell Killer and thus, his own murder. It's not an uninteresting premise but curiousity quickly becomes tedium as you work to make Ronan catch up with what you probably figured out just from reading those three sentences. Supernatural occurances in Salem equals witchcraft. In fact, reaching this level of obviousness and not overthinking things is probably the most difficult part of the game.While the game occasionally gives you action sequences involving sneaking around demons a la Metal Gear Solid, the primary bulk of the gameplay is exploring and using detective work to piece together the mystery of the Bell Killer. The kinds of puzzles you have to solve are similar to this: a body lies in front of you with a gunshot through the head. What weapon killed him: a gun, a knife or a rope? See what I mean about overthinking things? This isn't a trick question and the game is full of stupidity like this. One frequent puzzle that is honestly in the game is where you have to influence people to think about a certain topic so you can read their thoughts. You have to pick from a variety of subjects to get them to think about the Bell Killer. To do this, you pick the thought that is directly talking about the Bell Killer. There is no extra thought to this and the puzzle repeats FREQUENTLY throughout the game.The other gameplay elements aren't much better. The stealth sequences are absurdly easy and simply require you to move behind the demons who follow the exact same path without variation in rooms where there are, at most, four of them. There is also a collect-a-thon throughout the game where you pick up elements of backstory about a variety of topics like Ronan's life, Salem's history and other topics. There are over 200 of these collectables scattered throughout the relatively small game world and while it's fun to find these at first, it quickly becomes boring like the rest of the game due to very little reward for collecting them all.Due to the ease of completing the game and the stupidity of pretty much every character, the storyline is hardly fulfilling either. Some may enjoy making their way to the conclusion but you will likely guess what's going on after only a few hours of play time. Still, despite the bad gameplay, the controls felt great to me, using a 360 gamepad, and the camera worked surprisingly well, considering how much time is spent walking through walls. The sound is also decent with voiceovers ranging from passable to pretty decent. If you are looking for a mindless game to play through in a day or two, Murdered: Soul Suspect may be what you're looking for but if you're looking for something with even the slightest hint of meat to it, pass on this one. It will only disappoint."
,Recommended,233290,14631031,"Posted: 23 February, 2015",all,iceveiled,"A refreshing mystery game, light on action with some straight-forward navigational puzzles, and a solid narrative as far  as video games are concerned. There's some above average voice acting present here, with atmospheric and sometimes spooky visuals.The content and subject matter of Murdered: Soul Suspect is what makes it a breath of fresh air in a sea of violent action games.  How do people cope with their own deaths? You'll learn a lot about that subject if you take the time to talk to other ghosts in the game's world. Some are flat-out in denial, others have embraced it. Some are recently deceased, others are ancient ghosts, still troubled by their tragic (or not) fates. You'll encounter spirits that offer  side quests requiring you to help them figure out the circumstances  of how or why they died.  It's rather interesting if you're into that kind of thing.To nit pick, the game goes on for about an hour longer than it should, revisiting areas previously visited and therefore becoming a bit tedious, but the obligatory mystery genre twist at the end makes it worth it. There's no combat to speak of -- sometimes you have to dispatch ""demons"" which requires a bit of  stealth combined with quick time events -- that's the extent of Murdered: Soul Suspect's ""action"". These  scenarios are few and far between, but only serve to slow down your investigative process, and caused me to roll my eyes, particularly at the end of the game, when I just wanted to move forward with solving what I wanted to solve to complete the game.Murdured: Soul Suspect is not a perfect game but if you crave a break from shooting things in the face, instead gathering clues, solving mysteries and exercising the more analytical side of your brain, Murdered: Soul Suspect is for you."
