76561198064527406,Not Recommended,233290,13918633,"Posted: 9 January, 2015",all,TeeLight,"I didn't hate this game. I didn't love it, but I didn't hate it at all. And that says something, sorta. This game has a sort of charm in the same way the second Evil Dead had charm. It wasn't that good, but I couldn't help finding myself enjoying my time with it. The plot is thread bare, the gameplay is awkward, and the graphics aren't all that good considering how much of a resource hog the game is. I really liked the characters though and it was fun finding all the stuff.On the good side of things this game was a nice one to play after I played a series of pretty intense games. There's pretty much no way to get things wrong in this game. Ya' the clues rarely make sense for the problem given, but if you screw up ten times the game doesn't punish you for it. Sort of like a Sesame Street game. Minus Elmo. I also really liked the two main characters and especially their design. They were really poorly written, but I still found them strangely engaging.The technical glitches alone just about killed this game for me. Honestly they are completely unacceptable. There was a little while where I was pretty sure my graphics card was breaking. Turned out that the game just had some part of its code fail. Then the game crashed out of no where a couple of times and towards the end every time I tried to enter the judgement house the game would just stop running. It happened about six times in a row. I tried all kinds of things to make it work. This game was made by a rather large studio with an insane number of people working on it. I really don't get why it runs so poorly. That's ignoring things like major frame rate drops, character shadows appearing in places where there weren't any characters, and collectibles sometimes not appearing. There's no reason to charge money for a game that still has such major glitches in it.Then on top of that is the really awkward game play. I have no idea why they shoe horned in some of the mechanics that they did. The game is at it's best when I'm trying to find clues. It's at it's worst when I'm putting the clues together. The solution rarely made sense. Plus there's the teleporting mechanic that really only serves to pad out the game and the mechanic to find a bunch of the same thing in an area to get a story. The stories were good, and the art with them was worth it, it was just a terrible mechanic to make them an MMO style quest. Collect 14 gas cans to learn about the homeless guy that set himself on fire. Lame. The game would have stood on it's own if it would have just stuck to inspecting areas and making logical decisions based on what you found. Like a good point and click.This game has charm if you like B movies. If it's ever in the 5 dollar range I would say pick it up. With the bugs in the game I think at 5 dollars I could put up with them. Anything higher and I feel cheated. This isn't anything special enough to really make me want to pay more than that at this point. Maybe if they fixed the bugs it could be worth 10 dollars."
76561198021787422,Not Recommended,233290,15584463,"Posted: 27 April, 2015",all,Jewsus,Broken
76561198105513701,Recommended,233290,14841831,"Posted: 11 March, 2015",all,DayDead,"Just finished this game and I must say it worth its money.My rating: 9,5/10First of all, the Level Design is well layed out with a prety huge map to explore, not to mention that this game is based on exploration. There are many different paths you can take to reach a certain area, the indoor level design is gorgeous, many effects such as lens flares, particles/smoke, cool looking spectral city placed across the map with props all over it and the contrast between colors is tremendous. The more you explore, the more real information about the 1660 time you'll find and secondary cases you need to solve in order to obtain achivements and some creepy stories that are fun to hear or read.Secondly, speaking of textures now, the developers used a really wide range of textures, and the result? The boredom of seeing the same thing over and over again is excluded. Not only did they succeed in creating a sinister environment, but with the accompany of a Various library of sounds , they created a replica of a horror movie inwhich you choose the protagonist's moves.Thirdly, the animations, I must admit, could have been done a lot better. Such automatic, much less cool.Another aspect of the game I want to talk about is the combat system and the enemies. Besides the Killer Bell (the main enemy), are the demons. Yes, it appears that ghosts can be swallowed in by them...who would have thought? To kill one you need to follow this simple step: Go behind it and press the buttons that appears on your screen. Voila you just killed a badass looking demon. There are some demon's spawns on the floor which will make you cast a certain combination of keys the moment you step on it. If you fail, some demonic hands will drag you down (in hell maybe).Encountering a demon will only happen in a specific area full of teleportals. Although I used the Teleportals to travell across the map faster I also used them to hide from demons. They can't sense you in a teleportal.Possesing is a protagonist's ability to read people minds but you can't move with their bodies. Moreover, you can even posses a cat.Nevertheless the story is by far one of my favourites. I bought this game mainly for its level design and for the Dark, sinister and twisted story which caught my attention. You need to take decisions based on what you know so far, based on the recent findings and your logical interpretation.  I won't spoil the story don't worry, you really need to figure it out  yourself.The main character has a easily recognisable visual design and you must admit he's a badass looking ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ from the game's poster.All summed up, due to its story, level design including the textures,lighting,particles and lens flares, with a cold heart character I highly recommend this game."
