,Recommended,233290,11812836,"Posted: 21 August, 2014",all,Gongon,"Murdered: Soul Suspect is a story-driven game in which you take on the role of a recently deceased detective named Ronan. The basic gameplay consists of exploring your surroundings, searching for clues at crimescenes and piecing together the sequence of events based on the clues you have gathered. Also, going through walls is really neat.As you follow the trail of your killer you explore Salem to pick of trace memories of your life, help other lost souls ""move on"" and possess living being either to influence or read their minds (this sounds more awesome than it is in the game, and is only rarely useful/amusing).The combat in the game adds nothing to the gameplay and seems to only serve as a way to extend the length of the game. Fortunately there aren't that many combat sequences, but I still feel the game could have done without them.The main characters of the game are generally well motivated and fleshed out, but I feel the developers could have made better use of the mind-read ability to let us have a greater look into the supporting casts state of mind. They already established the mechanics, why not make use of them.Storywise there aren't really the biggest surprises, but it is coherently told and an enjoyable experience (in such a way the themes touched upon in the game can be considered enjoyable). The real draw of the game, for me at least, was figuring out the background of Ronan and his relationship with Julia. All their small victories.Finally, I have some technical issues at some points like the sound of cinematics coming from my speakers and all other sound coming from my headset and a point where no key I pressed registered in the game, but other than that a decent port. One thing though, unskippable intros and credits IS NOT OKAY!In short, if you like story-driven games where the characters are the focus, you might enjoy this game. If you're looking for a game with lots of action where you possess people and take over their bodies, look elsewhere."
