76561198021487969,Recommended,233290,11204231,"Posted: 12 July, 2014",all,Randomosity,"First of all, if you're looking for something unique to play that doesn't involve zombies or first-person shooting, then this should be right up your alley. Sure Murdered: Soul Suspect has it's flaws, but otherwise it's definitely an interesting murder-mystery with a side of ghosts and demons.The things that I liked:The graphics and voice acting was very good, better than some of the more well-known games. All of the characters had distinguishing features like freckles and blemishes. It was easier to care about the characters when they don't all have the same wooden faces when afraid.The story itself was interesting, maybe a little predictable at times, but there are still a few twists at the end. Investigating the crime scenes reminded me of L.A. Noire, and some of the puzzles were a little tricky, but nothing that couldn't be solved through trial and error. I also like the open world and how I could explore without automatically being pushed into the next misson.Now the things I didn't care for:As many people have stated, the saving system is one of the things that bring down this game. You can only have one save file, and there isn't anyway to backtrack to a previous chapter or mission. Even though it warns you at the end that you can't return to Salem, I feel like I should've gotten a warning at the museum since you can't go back for any missed artifacts. I might have been able to forgive this , if I was able to go back to a previous save. So really if you missed anything at the museum or Judgement House, you're out of luck. While I enjoyed Murdered, it didn't really have much replay value. Even though I wanted the artifacts and achievements, I didn't feel compelled to play again.I also have to agree that the demons are repetitive and somewhat tedious. While it was a good idea, the execution wasn't so good. They were more of a hindrance than a threat. The button pressing to destroy them can be awkward, and is one of the reasons why I died so much. Along those same lines, getting artifacts can also be awkward, as I found one clue, but I had to walk around it for five minutes, finding the perfect angle before I could pick it up.Overall, I enjoyed this game, and would recommend it. Yes, it is rather short, but still takes up some of your time. Even though I wished I wished I had waited until it was on sale, I don't regret buying this."
76561198076123272,Recommended,233290,11342550,"Posted: 20 July, 2014",all,millerandmolson,So far this game is very good.  It's a great detective game with a supernatural twist.  You are playing as Ronan who is now a ghost and he is trying to solve his own murder.  It's a great concept and very well done.  You search for clues in the different environments while avoiding or destroying demons.  You also have some side quests to do which involve helping lost souls pass on.  All in all I am very pleased with the game and glad I was able to pick it up during the summer sale.The only issue I have is there is no save feature.  It is auto saved so if you want to stop playing you have to get to a check point before you can stop or you will lose all your progress.
