76561198003031325,Not Recommended,233290,11076532,"Posted: 4 July, 2014",all,{PØN} Gallowsway,"Lots of ambition, poor implementation.What initially drew me in was the premise of the game:  A murder mystery ghost story who-done-it.  Instead, you find yourself trapped in a luke warm, predictable storyline with little flair.The investigation system, the setting and the like?  They are good ideas poorly implemented.There's only ever one soulution for each investigation, you know exactly how many clues they are, and it's very easy to figure out what happened in each situation before you conclude each investigation.  Solving a case means finding all the clues and then selecting the ""correct"" ones to move on.  The only difficulty in each investigation comes from trying to figure out which clues the developers wished you to reference in each investigation (the objectives aren't always clear).  After a few investigations, you pick up how the devs intended things to go, and it's basically a no-brainer from there.There's much more that I could go on about:  enemy encounters that can't decide if they are confrontational or stealth based, the very limited ""open"" world, and more.  Instead, let's take a look at what might have been.  The most depressing fact about the game is that you can easily see how this could have been a much better, very different game if they simply refined the experience.  Imagine:  a realized world with multiple fully fleshed out characters and places to explore.  Imagine:  being able to guess incorrectly on an investigation and wasting precious time following a false lead while there's a killer on the loose.  Imagine:  characters changing (killed, alienated and the like) based on your decisions.  Imagine:  multiple endings based on the decisions you've made.  Imagine:  meaningful sidequests that, while optional, might also give you access to different powers, resources and people.All of that just serves to make the whole experience more depressing.  If I could think this up not even halfway through the game, how could have the developers missed an opportunity like this?  Lack of budget/time/inspriation/testing?  Such a wasted opportunity!"
